# Rust Performance

Rust gives you zero-cost abstractions — but only if you do not accidentally pay for things you did not ask for.

## Profiling first

- Profile with `cargo flamegraph` or `perf` before optimising anything
- Use `criterion` for micro-benchmarks: `cargo bench` with `criterion::Criterion`
- Inspect assembly with `cargo asm` or `godbolt.org` when questioning whether a pattern is inlined
- Benchmark on release builds (`cargo bench` / `cargo build --release`) — debug builds are not representative

## Allocation

- Every `Box`, `Vec`, `String`, `Arc`, `Rc`, `HashMap` allocation has a cost — be conscious of allocations in hot paths
- Reuse buffers: pass `&mut Vec<u8>` / `&mut String` into functions to append rather than returning new allocations
- Use `Cow<'_, str>` / `Cow<'_, [T]>` when a function may or may not need to own its data
- Use `SmallVec` (crate) for collections that are almost always small and rarely overflow the stack buffer
- Avoid `format!()` in hot paths — write to a `Write` implementor directly or use `itoa`/`ryu` for numbers

## Iterators

- Iterator chains compile to tight loops — prefer them over manual `for` loops; they give the compiler more optimisation surface
- Use `.collect::<Vec<_>>()` only when you genuinely need a materialised collection; prefer chaining if you iterate once
- Use `iter()` / `iter_mut()` / `into_iter()` correctly — returning an owned iterator (`into_iter`) forces a move; prefer borrows when downstream only reads

## String handling

- Prefer `&str` slices over `String` ownership in functions that only read
- Use `String::with_capacity(n)` when the final size is known to avoid reallocations
- Use `write!` / `writeln!` to a `String` (which implements `Write`) rather than repeated `push_str`

## Struct layout

- Order struct fields largest to smallest to minimise padding (or derive `#[repr(C)]` deliberately)
- Use `#[repr(packed)]` only when marshalling wire formats — it disables alignment guarantees and can cause UB on some architectures
- Keep hot data together (data-oriented design): if you iterate over one field of all items, consider a struct-of-arrays layout

## Branch prediction & SIMD

- Annotate cold code paths with `#[cold]` and hot ones with `#[inline]` or `#[inline(always)]`
- Use `likely!` / `unlikely!` via `std::hint::likely` (stable 1.84+) for branch hints in tight loops
- For SIMD, use `std::simd` (portable SIMD, nightly) or `packed_simd` / vendor intrinsics only after profiling confirms the bottleneck

## Avoiding common pitfalls

```rust
// BAD — allocates a String on every call
fn is_prefix(s: &str) -> bool {
    s.to_lowercase().starts_with("http")
}
// GOOD — no allocation
fn is_prefix(s: &str) -> bool {
    s.len() >= 4 && s[..4].eq_ignore_ascii_case("http")
}

// BAD — repeated heap allocation in loop
for item in items {
    let s = format!("{}", item);
    sink.write_all(s.as_bytes())?;
}
// GOOD
let mut buf = String::new();
for item in items {
    buf.clear();
    write!(&mut buf, "{}", item)?;
    sink.write_all(buf.as_bytes())?;
}
```
